Description: CVE-2026-5704 - Fix -t/-x discrepancies enabling hidden file injection
 A flaw in GNU tar allows crafting malicious archives where non-data-bearing
 typeflags (symlink, char device, block device, FIFO, hard link) contain
 non-zero size fields, creating desynchronization between tar -t (listing) and
 tar -x (extraction). Files injected this way are invisible to pre-extraction
 inspection but silently written during extraction.
 .
 This backport adapts the upstream fix to tar 1.34's API. Key changes:
 - read_header: Do not treat LNKTYPE size as zero; read actual header size.
 - skip_member: Skip directory data too, track skipped status.
 - extract_archive: Always call skip_member after extraction for sync.
 - extract_dir/extract_file: Remove redundant skip_member calls.
 - purge_directory: Remove skip_member call (caller handles it).
 - extract_dir: When copying live stat for --no-overwrite-dir, preserve the
   archived member size so skip_member does not skip the next archive entry.
Origin: upstream, https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/tar.git/commit/?id=b8d8a61b25588caca4efaf9bdd2e3f1a49da77e3
Author: Paul Eggert <eggert@cs.ucla.edu>
Last-Update: 2026-04-10
